      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/03/a-lot-of-rhubarb/#comment-17414"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2014-04-26T01:36:49-04:00">Saturday, April 26, 2014 at 1:36 am</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>If you use 1/2 cup sugar (or any amount of sugar in anything) you may have ffewer than 50 Springs left. Yes, rhubarb is tart and needs sweetening, but white sugar (or brown sugar) are off limits for this 70 y/o who would be happy to have 20 Springs left. While honey isn&#39;t ideal, either, as it also contains too much sucrose, I do sweeten my rhubarb with it.  I use the honey sparingly and have learned to love the tartness of rhubarb.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
  <li id="comment-73330" class="comment even thread-even depth-1">
    <header class="comment--meta">
      <div class="vcard"><cite class="comment-author fn">Karen D.</cite></div>
      <a href="https://orangette.net/2010/03/a-lot-of-rhubarb/#comment-73330"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2019-06-01T21:09:10-04:00">Saturday, June 1, 2019 at 9:09 pm</time></a>    </header>

    
    <div class="comment--content">
      <p>Hi &#8211; I just wanted to share &#8211; So many people think that rhubarb is a Spring time, once a year delight.  I don&#8217;t stop harvesting mine until late October into November.  DO NOT CUT RHUBARB STALKS.  Pull them.  Yep &#8211; just pull them.  If you do that, you will have rhubarb into the Fall.  When you cut the stalk, new stalks cannot grow.  If you pull the stalk out(gentle tugging, it will let you know if it&#8217;s ready to be picked)a new stalk will form in that spot.  Try it  and you&#8217;ll have &#8216;barb all summer long.</p>
    </div>

      </li><!-- #comment-## -->
    </ol>
